    {
      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im working on a model and noticed my features have totally different scales. like one is 0-1 and another is 1000-5000. why do i actually need to normalize them before training? does it really matter that much?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, it absolutely matters because most machine learning algorithms are sensitive to the magnitude of input features, and without normalization, features with larger scales will dominate the learning process. This imbalance can cause the model to converge very slowly, or in some cases, fail to learn a meaningful pattern because the optimization landscape becomes distorted.\n\nThink of it like trying to weigh a feather next to a boulder; the scale (or the algorithm) will naturally focus entirely on the boulder and ignore the feather, leading to poor performance on the small-scale features.\n\nIn your case, the feature ranging from 1000 to 5000 will likely overshadow the one between 0 and 1, causing gradients to be unstable during training. Normalizing them to a common scale (like 0-1 or standardizing to mean 0 and variance 1) ensures that each feature contributes equally, allowing the model to learn effectively regardless of its original units.\n\nWithout this step, your model's convergence will be sluggish and its final accuracy will likely be suboptimal compared to a normalized version. It's a standard best practice that almost always improves training stability and speed.",
